observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management: 

Submit RPCPPE for CIP account as of year-end;



Reconcile RPCPPE with CAO records;



Facilitate the disposal of fully depreciated and unserviceable PPE items, and prepare adjusting entries in books, including the donated PPE items;



Maintain complete PCs; and



Henceforth, strictly comply with the provisions of COA Circular Nos. 2022-004 and 2020-006 dated May 31, 2022 and January 21, 2020, respectively, and IPSAS 17.

We recommended that Management monitor and reconcile the Inventories account and direct:

The Officer-in-Charge (OIC)-OGS to –

Require the end-users and property custodians to immediately submit the utilization reports/distribution lists and other documents, prepare the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI), and submit the same together with the with Requisition and Issue Slip (RIS) to the CAO on a weekly basis for the computation of the cost of the supplies issued; and



Complete the required information in the Report of Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) according to the instructions provided in the MNGAS for LGUs.

The City Accountant to – 

Assign personnel to periodically monitor and coordinate with the OGS for the reconciliation of the inventory accounts;

Coordinate with the OGS to identify, resolve the nature and causes of discrepancies, and reconcile the balances between the (subsidiary ledgers) SLs and RPCI amounting to P2,411,894,706.52;

Reconcile the discrepancy between the SLs and Supplies Ledger Cards (SLCs) amounting to P448,980,289.51;

Facilitate the timely recording of the issuances in the books; and

Update the SLC of each inventory item immediately after recording the submitted SSMI, and provide adjustments to reflect the latest Inventory balance in the books.

We recommended that Management require the OIC-Office of the Schools Division Superintendent to:

Facilitate a thorough analysis of an effective and feasible allocation of the planned programs/projects/ activities (PPAs) which should include an assessment of whether the PPAs can be accomplished within the scheduled timeframe to achieve the optimal utilization of the SEF;

Establish a new and effective monitoring system to make sure that the PPAs are being implemented on time;



Coordinate with the concerned end-user offices/departments for the progress of the procurement activities; and 



Ensure that the quarterly monitoring and evaluation reports coincide with the records of the CAO relative to the utilization of the fund, and duly approved/signed by the concerned officials.

We recommended that the OIC-OGS – 

Avoid using phrases like first partial, proposed construction, payment for the cost of materials and labor, etc. in describing the infrastructure assets in the RPCPPE-Particulars column;

Maintain copies of DOAS and TDRP to serve as permanent files supporting the PPE accounts in RPCPPE;

We recommended that the City Mayor direct:
The City Accountant to –
Require the persons in-charge of recording the PPE in the SL, and preparing the LS, to coordinate, communicate and collaborate with each other to reconcile their records;
Reconcile the accounting records with the OGS RPCPPE to address the noted deficiencies;
The Officer-in-Charge (OIC)-OGS to obtain the TCTs of all City-owned parcels of land to establish absolute ownership and mitigate possible legal risks; and
The CAO and OGS to facilitate the review, verification, and reconciliation of all PPE accounts, and to follow strictly the procedures prescribed in COA Circular No. 2020-006 for the one-time cleansing of the PPE balances.

We reiterated our previous year’s recommendation that the City Mayor direct:
The OIC-OGS to –
Complete the details of the inventories in the RPCI according to the instructions provided in Annex 48 of the MNGAS;
Direct all supply and property officers/custodians to submit on time the SSMI together with the RIS to the CAO;
The City Accountant to –
Reconcile, in coordination with the OGS, to identify and resolve the nature and causes of the noted discrepancies;
Monitor and coordinate with OGS on the timely submission of SSMI and facilitate the immediate recording of issuances in the books; and
Update the SLC of each inventory item immediately after recording the submitted SSMI and provide adjustments to reflect the latest inventory balances in the books.

We reiterated our previous year’s recommendation that the City Mayor direct the City Accountant to:
Demand from the concerned SDO to submit complete liquidation documents and require them to return/refund immediately the unused CA;
Withhold the salary of the SDO who failed to liquidate their CA within the prescribed period;
Stop the practice of approving additional CA to SDO whose previous CA has not been liquidated; and
Prepare a monitoring report in the granting and liquidation of the CA.

We recommended that the City Mayor address the deficiencies by directing:
The City Assessor to implement a standardized PIN pursuant to the MRPAAO issued by the BLGF in CAO and CTO records/reports; undertake corrective measures to prevent identical PIN in the AR; rectify and adjust accordingly the assessment of properties with MV that are not in conformity and/or aligned with the specified SMV prescribed by City Ordinance No. 6; and to execute the necessary updating in the AR of all real properties within the jurisdiction of the City to enable the CTO to give complete reports to the CAO for a more accurate and reliable balances of the RPT and SET Receivable accounts as of year-end;
The City Treasurer to include the 3,200 properties in the set-up of RPT and SET receivables and to refund the taxes collected to previous property owner, now owned by the City;
The City Assessor and City Treasurer to conduct a thorough/complete reconciliation of the Certified List of Receivables and the AR to identify and correct the inconsistencies in the property listings and assessed values; and
The Head-MISO to make the necessary adjustments in the computerized system.

We recommended that the City Mayor direct:
The City Accountant  to –
Exert efforts in locating the records relative to the collection of the building permit fees and other charges for CYs 2013 to 2018 and remit the corresponding 5% share to the DPWH;
Recognize in full the amount due to DPWH as established by the concerned offices. Consequently, effect the necessary adjusting entries resulted from the under accrual of the amount to reflect the correct balances presented in the financial statement as at year-end;
The City Treasurer to regularly remit the full amount representing the 5% share of DPWH to the account of the DPWH Secretary under Special Account No. 154 thru the Bureau of Treasury pursuant to the provision of JMC No. 001; and
The OIC-OBO and Head-MISO to continue coordinating with the City Treasurer and City Accountant in establishing the computation of the 5% share from the above-mentioned “Other Charges.”

We recommended that the City Mayor direct:
The City Accountant to include all the expenditures charged to the LDRRMF in the RUD of DRRMF;
The Head-CPDO to strictly monitor the implementation of the City’s priority PPAs;
The Head-CDRRMO to coordinate with the Head-CPDO and City Accountant to effectively monitor the implementation and utilization of the targeted PPAs and to prepare the complete RUD, respectively; and
The Chairperson-BAC to expedite the procurement process to ensure the timely implementation of the planned PPAs and to avoid under-utilization of the LDRRMF.

We reiterated our previous year’s recommendation that the City Mayor direct:
The City Accountant to –
Expedite the reconciliation of the 14 inactive tax sub-accounts and provide details for the balances which were carried over during the accounting system transition;
Remit the amount of P1,619,158.54 under the GF and SEF for CY 2023;
Closely coordinate with the CTO for the immediate remittance of the CGT and DST totaling P453,600.00 which have been outstanding for more than three years; and
Strictly remit the exact amount of taxes withheld within the prescribed period pursuant to the aforecited BIR regulations;
The City Treasurer to -
Replace the stale checks totaling P453,600.00 and coordinate with the CAO to facilitate the immediate remittance of the same to the BIR; and
Monitor the release of checks to avoid being stale and incurrence of penalties, surcharges and interest in case of delayed remittances to the BIR.

We reiterated our prior year’s recommendations that Management direct:
The OIC-General Services Officer to –
Submit immediately to COA a copy of the final and approved RPCPPE for CY 2021 covering the entire PPE items of the City and comply with the deadline set forth under the MNGAS for LGUs;
Forward a complete file of Property Cards for each PPE category to COA for review;
Prepare the RPCPPE in accordance with the prescribed format indicating the appropriate and correct details, such as property description, location, condition and acquisition cost;
Use the correct classification in the RPCPPE under SEF in lieu of inappropriate categories, such as “Other Supplies Expenses,” “Office Supplies Expenses, ” “Office Supplies Inventory,” “Other Inventory Items,” “Other Assets,” “OSME Other Supplies,” “Electricity,” “Donation,” “Medical, Dental and Laboratory Supplies Expenses,” “Furniture and Office Equipment,” Textbook and Instructional Materials Expenses,” “No account,” and “Tools;”
Stop using phrases like first partial, proposed construction, payment for the cost of materials and labor, etc. in the Description column of infrastructure assets;
Record the items costing below the P15,000.00 capitalization threshold as inventories and issue the corresponding Inventory Custodian Slips;
Submit a copy of the final RPCPPE to CAO for the reconciliation of records, and adjustment of the identified discrepancies to arrive at the correct PPE balances;
Provide details/breakdown for the PPE items reported as beginning balances totaling P3,938,012,337.48; and
Facilitate the transfer of ownership for the 113 land items still not in the name of City Government of Pasig.
The OIC-City Accountant to –
Facilitate reconciliation of PPE balances in the General Ledger against the reported balances in the RPCPPE as of 
December 31, 2021; and
Maintain updated Real Property/PPE/CIP Ledger Cards for each class of PPE complete with proper description/details and reconcile the same with the GL balances.

We reiterated our previous year’s recommendation that Management instruct:
The OIC-General Services Officer to –
Regularly submit on a weekly basis the SSMI together with the original RIS to the CAO;
Update and submit the SCs for reconciliation of balances against the SLCs of the CAO;
Obtain from CAO the list of inventories purchased from CYs 2019 to 2021 under the TF amounting to P19,842,515.00, conduct physical count and submit the RPCI immediately to COA;
The OIC-City Accountant to –
Reconcile the balances between the SLs and RPCI amounting to P  3,081,013,250.29;
Reconcile the balances between the SLs and SLCs amounting to P1,198,695,218.34;
Review the SLs for inventory accounts with non-moving items in the GF and make the appropriate adjustments, if warranted;
Monitor and coordinate with GSO on the timely submission of the weekly SSMIs, together with the original RIS, and facilitate the immediate recording of issuances in the books; and
Update the SLC of each inventory item immediately after recording the submitted SSMIs, and provide adjustments to reflect the latest Inventory balances in the books.

We reiterated our previous year’s recommendation that Management instruct -
The OIC-City Accountant to exert extra efforts to obtain the necessary documents, including debit and credit memo from the bank to support the recording of the unidentified reconciling items and effect the needed adjustments for fair presentation of the balances of the Cash in Bank and other related accounts;
The City Treasurer to:
Consolidate the total PhilHealth remittances of P311,124,205.36, which include the prior years’ collections totaling P287,625,402.92; and immediately reconcile the same with the CAO records;
Stop the issuance of official receipts for PhilHealth remittances since these were directly credited to the bank account of the City; and
Coordinate with the CAO for the reconciliation and proper adjustment of unidentified variances resulting from online and card collections.

We recommended that Management require:
The OIC-City Accountant to –
Record the trust receipts in the proper fund using the correct accounts;
Prepare the bank reconciliation statements for the Trust Fund;
Submit the utilization reports together with all the supporting documents to COA pursuant to Section 6.5 of COA Circular 
No. 94-013;
The City Treasurer to furnish the CAO of the necessary and pertinent documents relative to the funds granted; and
The Head-Finance Office of the PLP to submit the liquidation reports required by the CHED for the funds granted, course through the CAO, and approved by the City Mayor in compliance with the MOA.

The City Accountant  – 

Demand submission of copies of CR, DR and credit/debit card transactions from the banks in the amounts of P394,382,735, P40,419,467 and P75,540,025, respectively, for the period from CYs 2016 to 2020;

Henceforth, make arrangement with the depository banks to provide copies of CM and DM to the City on a monthly basis or on a more convenient frequency to properly document the recording of the items in the books of accounts;

Adjust the double/ under/erroneous recording of the transactions noted in audit;

Effect the necessary adjustments as soon as differences between the bank statements and accounting records are detected for fair presentation of the balances of Cash in Bank and other related accounts; and

The City Treasurer consolidate the PhilHealth remittances amounting to P287,625,403 which were received by various collecting offices of the City for the period covering CYs 2016 to 2020 and submit the same to CAO to facilitate reconciliation of the records. Moreover, stop the practice of issuing ORs for PhilHealth remittances since these are directly credited to the bank account of the City.

The General Services Officer (GSO) – 

Expedite the completion of the physical count of all properties owned by the City; 


Prepare a reliable RPCPPE for all PPE accounts in accordance with the prescribed format indicating the complete details, such as the property description, condition, balances per card, balances on hand per count and other relevant information;

Submit the RPCPPE to the CAO to facilitate reconciliation of the records, and to adjust the identified discrepancies to arrive at the correct PPE balances;

Submit RPCPPE to COA in the prescribed format, complete with all the details not later than January 31 of each year pursuant to the MNGAS for LGUs;

Provide details/breakdown for the PPE items reported in the summary report totaling P230,717,503, and for the noted discrepancy in the Land account amounting to P421,446,231;


Avoid using phrases like first partial, proposed construction, payment for the cost of materials and labor, etc. in describing the infrastructure assets in the RPCPPE-Particulars column;

Maintain copies of DOAS and TDRP to serve as permanent files supporting the PPE accounts in RPCPPE; 


Coordinate with the concerned office to facilitate the transfer of the parcels of land which are not yet registered in the name of the City; and


Maintain a complete file of Property Cards for each PPE category as listed in the accounting records, and ensure that the balances therein agree with RPCPPE and book balances.

The City Accountant  – 

Facilitate reconciliation of PPE balances in the General Ledger against the reported balances in the RPCPPE and provide the necessary adjustments for the variance noted in audit in the amount of P8,327,394,733;

Conduct reconciliation of the balances of PPE accounts in PPELCs/RPLCs and PCs on a regular basis; and

Maintain updated PPE and Real Property Ledger Cards for each class of PPE complete with proper description/details.

Henceforth, the GSO and CAO to comply with COA Circular 2020-006 dated  January 31, 2020, for the one- time cleansing of the PPE accounts.

The City Accountant –

Identify and locate the records of the projects implemented during CYs 2016 to 2018 which are still in the CIP accounts;




Prioritize the transfer of completed projects By Administration and include the accompanying labor costs and other attributable costs for supplies and materials issued to the respective infrastructure projects;



Reclassify the completed project, Proposed Pasig City Hall Building Security Plan Pasig City Hall to Buildings account and record the Accumulated Depreciation;




Recompute the balance of payables due to contractors, adjust the CIP and Accounts Payable accounts for the noted projects; and



Closely monitor the CIP account and maintain updated CIP Ledger Cards pursuant to the provisions of the MNGAS.

The GSO –

Submit immediately to COA the duly approved consolidated/final RPCI as of December 31, 2020; 




Prepare Stock Cards for all items of inventories and facilitate reconciliation with the SLCs of the CAO; 

Regularly submit the SSMI together with RIS to the CAO for the timely recording of the issuances of the inventories in the books; 

Comply with the requirement of the MNGAS on the conduct of physical count of inventory items by type semestrally and submit the RPCI to the Auditor not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively; and

Monitor the distribution of goods to the end-users to ensure that the received goods tally with the distribution list and the issuances recorded in SSMI;

The City Accountant –

Prepare and maintain SLC for each inventory item for all funds indicating the complete information including the corresponding expense account and ensure that the balances reconcile with the GL;

Review the SLCs for inventory accounts with non-moving items and make the appropriate adjustments, if warranted;



Coordinate with the OGS for the reconciliation of the SLCs and SCs on a regular basis; and


Properly classify expenses according to nature and use to fairly present the accounts in the financial statements.

Stop the practice of approving additional cash advances to AOs unless the previous CA granted to them has been liquidated to avoid sanctions imposed in Section 128 of PD No. 1445; 




Strictly enforce liquidation of the outstanding CAs of the City’s officers and employees who are still in active service by sending demand letters requiring submission of the liquidation documents for the settlement of their accounts; 



If no settlement was received, require the Human Resource Development Office to enforce the provisions of the COA Circular on the liquidation of CAs, particularly the withholding of salaries of the accountable officers who fail to liquidate their CAs within the prescribed period;

Exert earnest effort in locating the accountable officer who has been AWOL, and require settlement/refund of the CA;

Refrain from securing CA for the payment of regular expenditures incurred in the normal operation of the City;


Require the CAO to devise an effective monitoring system for the grant and liquidation of CAs to avoid accumulation of outstanding receivables; and

Grant cash advances for cash gifts and other allowances on the first week of December to enable the Accountable Officers to submit the liquidation reports before the closing of the books.

Collect relevant documents and request authority from the COA to write-off the receivables which are non-moving for more than 
10 years, after all the remedies have been exhausted, in accordance with Sections 7.4 and 8 of COA Circular No. 2016-005;




For those who have already resigned or retired with outstanding balances, issue demand letters for the settlement thereof.  Otherwise, require the refund of the amounts from the officials and employees responsible before release  of their clearances; 

Notify the concerned employee who is still in the active service for the settlement of the outstanding obligation; and


Instruct the City Accountant to consider recognition of allowance for impairment of receivables in accordance with International Public Sector Accounting Standards 21.

Provide a concrete policy for the subject program of the Pasig City Division of City Schools to facilitate its smooth implementation;




Issue the appropriate PARs for the laptops distributed to the end-users to determine the persons responsible in case of loss of the said properties; and

Instruct the Head-Division of City Schools to prepare post-activity report for every program implemented to determine the success of the activity.

The City Accountant  -

Remit the full amount of taxes withheld during the month on or before the 10th day of the next month to avoid any variances, and hold the person/s responsible for the delayed remittances to personally answer for the penalties and surcharges that may be imposed by BIR; 




Prepare monthly schedule of Due to BIR accounts to monitor the amounts withheld and remitted and to determine the cause of the noted abnormal balances; 

Trace back the details and prepare schedule of the net over-remittance totaling P451,700 pertaining to November 2019 and prior years’ withholding taxes to support the possible claim of tax refund or tax credit from BIR; and



Recheck/review the accuracy of the total amount of deductions and the amount to be remitted to BIR every month to avoid under and/or over payment.

The GSO –

Exert more effort to come up with a more reliable RPCPPE complete with specifications and land use based on physical count and reconcile the same with the accounting records;

Maintain a Property Card (PC) for each land item complete with details on the date of acquisition, actual land use and other necessary information and ensure that these are reconciled with the RPCPPE;

Initiate the transfer of 97 parcels of land in the name of the City; and 


The City Accountant – 

Coordinate with the GSO in reconciling records with the physical count; 

Maintain and update the Real Property Ledger Cards and ensure these are reconciled with the General Ledger;

The Inventory Committee –

Conduct regular and complete physical count of all properties of the City;




Prepare the corresponding RPCPPE in accordance with the prescribed format indicating the complete details on the whereabouts, condition and other relevant information relative to the PPE;

The General Services Officer – 

Properly maintain the Property Cards for each PPE category listed in the accounting records and ensure that the balances shown thereon agree with the prepared RPCPPE and the book balances;




Prepare the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) to be the basis in dropping from the books the unserviceable properties and follow the prescribed procedures in the disposal of PPE; 

Issue and update PARs for all PPE items, starting with the current and recent years’ acquisitions until all items are covered therewith and thereafter, renew/update the PAR every three years or whenever there is transfer of accountability;

The City Accountant –

Properly prepare and maintain the required PPE Ledger Cards for each class of PPE, listing therein the data as to its acquisition, description, custody, useful life and other necessary information;

Prepare the CIP Ledger Cards to be able to track the accumulated cost of construction per asset type;

Coordinate with the City Engineer’s Office for the issuance of certificate of project completion and acceptance for the transfer of the CIP Accounts to the proper asset accounts and computation of depreciation expense and accumulated depreciation;

Coordinate with GSO in the reconciliation of accounting records and physical inventory; 

Include the cost of improvement/extension/renovation to the improved/extended/renovated asset to enable monitoring of additional costs in maintaining the assets that could serve as input in the future when a decision has to be made over the existence of such asset;

Add the cost of labor and materials procured separately to the PPE where they are directly attributable to arrive at the actual/total cost of such PPE;

Ensure that the classification of assets in the Schedule of Depreciation is updated each time that reclassification is made. Moreover, see to it that the correct reckoning date and estimated useful life of the asset is used in computing depreciation; and

Abide by the provisions of the applicable COA Circulars in computing for depreciation and prepare the Schedule of Depreciation properly, ensure that the required information are provided, such as the carrying value and the accumulated depreciation that should agree with the controlling account balances so that discrepancies could be readily identified and corrected.

The Inventory Committee conduct a physical count of the supplies and materials and prepare the RPCIs for two semesters in the prescribed format; and ensure that the balances are reconciled with the accounting records;

The Central Supply Officer -

Properly maintain the SCs for all types of inventory, fill up all the required information and regularly reconcile them to the SLCs;




The City Accountant – 

Maintain SLCs for each inventory item, indicating the complete information on the specific IPSAS accounts they were recorded and year-end balances and ensure that the total of their balances reconcile with the GL.

The City Accountant –

Coordinate with the Human Resource Development Officer (HRDO) in enforcing the provisions on the liquidation of cash advances, particularly the withholding of salaries of accountable officers who fail to liquidate their cash advances within the prescribed period;

Require all accountable officers to liquidate their cash advances at the end of each year or render a report of payments made so they can be recognized during the year that they were incurred and balances of affected accounts are reliably presented in the financial statements; 

Devise an effective monitoring system for the grant and liquidation of cash advances and ensure that all transactions related thereto are correctly recorded.

The Inventory Committee –

Conduct regular and complete physical count of all properties of the City; 




Prepare the corresponding RPCPPE in accordance with the prescribed format indicating the whereabouts, condition and other relevant information relative to the PPE;

Submit the report within the prescribed period;

The City General Services Officer – 

Maintain properly accomplished property cards for each category of PPE listed in the accounting records and ensure that the balances shown thereon agree with the prepared RPCPPE and the book balances;

